======================================================================
PART 5: FORBIDDEN RESIDUE PERSISTENCE ANALYSIS
======================================================================

  By the reduction theorem, I(x) mod p = I(x mod p) mod p.
  So we only need to study I(x) for x = 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6.

  I(0) = 1 always.
  I(1) = 1 + α₁ + α₂ (total independent sets)
  I(2) = H
  I(3), I(4), I(5), I(6) determined by (α₁, α₂) at n≤8.

  The FORBIDDEN RESIDUES of H mod p are the most important.
  All other I(x) mod p reduce to these via the reduction theorem.

  H mod  3: n=5 forbidden []  →  n=6 forbidden []
  H mod  5: n=5 forbidden [2]  →  n=6 forbidden []
  H mod  7: n=5 forbidden [0]  →  n=6 forbidden [0]
  H mod 11: n=5 forbidden [6, 7, 8, 10]  →  n=6 forbidden []
  H mod 13: n=5 forbidden [4, 6, 7, 8, 10, 12]  →  n=6 forbidden [8]

  I(1) mod  3: n=5 forbidden []  →  n=6 forbidden []
  I(1) mod  5: n=5 forbidden [4]  →  n=6 forbidden []
  I(1) mod  7: n=5 forbidden [4]  →  n=6 forbidden []
  I(1) mod 11: n=5 forbidden [0, 4, 9, 10]  →  n=6 forbidden []

  I(3) mod  2: n=5 forbidden []  →  n=6 forbidden []
  I(3) mod  5: n=5 forbidden [0]  →  n=6 forbidden []
  I(3) mod  7: n=5 forbidden [3]  →  n=6 forbidden []
  I(3) mod 11: n=5 forbidden [3, 6, 9, 10]  →  n=6 forbidden [9]

